                            <tls:text>
                                <tls:srcline title="國語" target="#KR2e0001_tls_003-32a.49" pos="1">賓胥無、
                    </tls:srcline>
                                <tls:line title="" transl-id="" src=""/>
                            </tls:text>
                            <form corresp="#賓:賓 #uuid-c875981b-9f25-4be1-81cc-f5e34e7998e4 #uuid-5de002ac-c1a1-4519-a177-4a3afcc155bb" orig="">
                                <orth>賓胥無</orth>
                                <pron xml:lang="zh-Latn-x-pinyin">賓 xū
 wú</pron>
                            </form>
                            <sense corresp="#uuid-282f3e6c-2bf8-4a60-af3e-6c2bf87a604f">
                                <gramGrp>
                                    <pos>N</pos>
                                    <tls:syn-func corresp="#uuid-c43c0bab-2810-42a4-a6be-e4641d9b6632">NPpr</tls:syn-func>
                                </gramGrp>
                                <def>Bīn Xūwú 賓胥無 (7th century) was a tailor in the court of &gt;Duke Huan of Qi 齊桓公, mentioned in HF 37. GUAN 18.1 has him - together with &gt;Xi Peng 隰朋 (d. 645)- remonstrating with &gt;Duke Huan of Qi. Throughout GUAN he is celebrated as one of the da fu 大夫 “dignitaries” (including prime minister &gt;Guan Zhong 管仲 (d. 643)) who are taken to have been instrumental in the rise and the political success of Duke Huan of Qi. [GUAN 26, 51, 81, 83]</def>
                            </sense>
                            <tls:metadata resp="#CH" created="2020-04-17T04:10:36.443+09:00">
                                <respStmt>
                                    <resp>added</resp>
                                    <name notBefore="2020-04-17T04:10:36.443+09:00">CH</name>
                                </respStmt>
                            </tls:metadata>
                        </tls:ann>
                    </seg>
                    <seg xml:id="KR2e0001_tls_004-330a.4">
                        <line>智襄子戲韓康子而侮段規。
                    </line>
                        <tls:ann xmlns:tls="http://hxwd.org/ns/1.0" concept="MALES OF HAN" concept-id="uuid-f12a243f-cb0f-4be9-ab5e-2557d4291bb6" xml:id="uuid-7826e436-62f5-4154-a6e4-3662f56154cd">
                            <link target="#KR2e0001_tls_004-330a.4 #uuid-25de5028-ab6b-4753-9e50-28ab6bd753c9"/>
                            <tls:text>
                                <tls:srcline title="國語" target="#KR2e0001_tls_004-330a.4" pos="10">智襄子戲韓康子而侮段規。
                    </tls:srcline>
                                <tls:line title="" transl-id="" src=""/>
                            </tls:text>
                            <form corresp="#uuid-bec1f225-61d2-487f-9331-123d114a955d #uuid-aeae44dd-32f9-4c1c-8720-12903bd2d330" orig="">
                                <orth>段規</orth>
                                <pron xml:lang="zh-Latn-x-pinyin">duàn guī</pron>
                            </form>
                            <sense corresp="#uuid-25de5028-ab6b-4753-9e50-28ab6bd753c9">
                                <gramGrp>
                                    <pos>N</pos>
                                    <tls:syn-func corresp="#uuid-c43c0bab-2810-42a4-a6be-e4641d9b6632">NPpr</tls:syn-func>
                                </gramGrp>
                                <def>Duàn Guī 段規 (fl. 453) was a ministerial adviser in Han 韓 to Han Kangzi 韓康子 and was instrumental in the murder of the Earl of Zhi 智伯 in 453. In ZGC Zhao 1 Duan Gui advises the ruler of the state of Han against acceding to demands for land by the Earl of Bo. According to GY Jinyu 9  and SY 5.27 Duan Gui is instrumental in the murder of the Earl.</def>
                            </sense>
                            <tls:metadata resp="#CH" created="2020-04-18T03:28:49.25+09:00">
                                <respStmt>
                                    <resp>added</resp>
                                    <name notBefore="2020-04-18T03:28:49.25+09:00">CH</name>
                                </respStmt>
                            </tls:metadata>
                        </tls:ann>
